ough it is facing different challenges and opportunities than elsewhere. Living on a continent characterized by highly diverse patterns of culture, language, history, and relations to Jews, European Jewry mirrors that kaleidoscopic diversity. This volume explores such key questions as the new roles for Jews in Europe; models of Jewish community organization in Europe; concepts of diaspora and galut; a European-Jewish way of life in the era of globalization; and European Jews' relationship to Israel and to non-Jews. Some contributions highlight experiences of Jews in Britain, Sweden, Norway, Hungary, Austria, Germany, and the Netherlands. Helping us to understand the special and common characteristics of European Jewry, this collection offers a valuable contribution to the continued rebuilding of Jewish life in the postwar era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xInfluence. 0aJewszEuropexHistoryy20th century. 0aJewszEuropexHistoryy21st century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Jewish Studies.2bisacsh1 aBodemann, Y. Michal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDencik, Lars, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDämmig, Lara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGalchinsky, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlapheck, Elisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLawton, Clive A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeveson, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeveson, Ian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLustig, Sandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLustig, Sandra, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/v